@@eThe Roc Road: Two Cities Arguing Over the Best Leash@@N

@@yFrom the Garden Ledger, Diplomatic Observation File@@N
@@dAnnotated by the Ember Warden Border Watch@@N

The @@eRoc Road@@N runs between @@yMidgaard@@N and @@yKiess@@N. One governs
by stone law. The other by adaptive commerce. Between them, a road
of layered arguments about the proper way to @@rcontrol@@N passage.
Neither has asked whether control is @@ynecessary@@N.

On the eastern half, Midgaard carves its imprint in stone: patrol
relays, checkpoint oath recitations, the @@WThree Civic Oaths@@N at
every shift change. Boundary sigils repainted even when manpower
prevents repairs, because the @@WOath of Stone@@N requires visible
jurisdiction. The @@yappearance@@N of governance matters more than
the @@greality of care@@N.

On the western half, Kiess convoy marshals manage flow through
shared liability pools. More @@ypractical@@N, but no less controlling.
The marshal decides who moves and when. Kiess is honest about
calling it logistics rather than @@rlaw@@N.

The @@rCrossroads@@N in the center is where the argument bleeds.
Charter boundaries blur. Violence spikes when either side reaches
for unilateral control.

The Garden Ledger Clerks study the Roc Road the way healers study
illness. @@yMidgaard@@N asks: @@W"Who has lawful right to command?"@@N
@@yKiess@@N asks: @@y"What keeps goods alive to arrive tomorrow?"@@N
Rakuen asks the question neither will consider: @@g"What if nobody
needs to command at all?"@@N

Kiess was built on the ruins of @@yEvermeet@@N, with a founding clause:
no sealed warrant from a predecessor shall bind a citizen. The Bloom
Pavilion respects this -- the closest any city has come to Rakuen's
own rejection of inherited obligation. But Kiess replaced warrants
with @@ycontracts@@N, and contracts are warrants with better
@@rmarketing@@N.

Rakuen has no road like this. We have the @@gGarden Walk@@N, where
stewards rotate and no one posts a sentry because the walk belongs
to everyone. When Midgaard's resettlement convoys brought displaced
families south during the @@rcontainment era@@N, those families arrived
along roads governed by oaths and liability pools -- and arrived
@@rexhausted@@N, every mile having cost them a toll or a stamp.

We offered them the Garden Walk. No oath required. No stamp demanded.
Just a path, and someone at the end with @@gwater@@N.

That is the difference the Roc Road cannot teach, because neither
city at its ends believes a road can exist without a @@rledger@@N.
